This is my planning board, where every book I write has its ideas and shapes and characters and structures and storylines laid out. 

It has everything essential to the book on it, and I’ve found over the years that I can’t work properly without it. 

But one of my favourite moments in the whole process is taking everything down once a manuscript has been delivered. 

It’s a sort of watershed day, where I also try and tidy up my office, which by this stage of writing will always be - to be fair to it - an absolutely wretched filthy overfilled disorganised disgrace.

Today I took down WOLVES OF WINTER, since the book is now handed in, and being edited for publication this October. 

It was interesting to see how the shape and themes of the book had changed as I was writing. And to chart the creeping madness as the deadline loomed, reflected in the degenerating Sharpie scrawls. 

A lot of the stuff on the board didn’t make it into the book, or did, but not as i thought it would, or will be moved in the final book of the Essex Dogs trilogy. Or won’t. 

Anyway, it was a satisfying job to do and now the wall is clean and clear. Soon I’ll start filling it up with material for the next one. 

NB I guess the chances are you couldn’t give a shit about this. You’re probably right.

NEW SHOW!! #SexABonkersHistory @historyuk 

Coming later this year 

Sex is the one thing we can be certain human beings have done throughout the whole of history. It’s a fascinating way to take a romp through the millennia, from the Ancient Egyptians to swingers in the 1970s, and up to the wonders of the digital age we live in today. @noholdenback is a dream host – she’s a great laugh, who’s always ready with a penetrating question and a fresh take on the past. Meanwhile, I’ve had a blast throwing myself into some pretty weird and wild situations – all in the name of research. It’s the most historical fun I’ve had with (most of) my clothes on.

Today I went in to 10 Downing St to meet the totally ideal Year 6 cohort from Barrowford Primary School and help @akshatamurty_official run a history workshop focused on writing speeches in a time of crisis. 

We spoke about Winston Churchill coming to office in 1940 (sort of medieval, ish) and the children worked superbly in groups to compose their own speeches to galvanise the nation and decry tyranny. Fair to say Hitler got it in the neck and we were all quite hyped up by the end. 

The tour of Downing Street afterwards was completely fascinating. 

In picture 3, Mia is explaining to me that she has invented a new form of mathematics in which 1x1=6. Can’t lie, it sounded convincing. Props also to the young man who said he assumed I was Mrs Murty’s bodyguard. 

Glorious stuff. I loved every second. Loved it.

DAN JONES & FANS CRUSADER SPAIN ADVENTURE! 
April 6-13, 2024

Join popular British historian, author, broadcaster, and award-winning journalist DAN JONES on an adventure through Spain to experience the history of the Crusades. Dan will present information from his book “Crusaders” in places where the stories and action ACTUALLY TOOK PLACE! Dan will give you the information, show you around, and answer your questions! 

The itinerary includes (but is not limited to):

* Crusader history in Seville
* Flamenco show
* Ronda— an ancient Moorish stronghold
* Wine-tastings
* Cordoba and Madinat al-Zahara with its ruins
* Granada— the site of many crusader battles
* Olive tasting and snacks with a local olive producer
* The palace of Alhambra (once occupied by Ferdinand and Isabella)

AND MORE!

Visit AuthorFanTravel.com to learn more and claim your spot!
